Contribution of Africa's sub-regions to Maize and Wheat production from 2001 to 2020¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this investigation I wanted to look at how the different sub-regions in Africa fared in terms of maize and wheat and maize production to determine which regions would need the most support.

The agricultural Gross Production Index (GPI) is one of the methods used to determine amount of food production. This Index is prepared by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO). The FAO indices of agricultural production show the relative level of the aggregate volume of agricultural production for each year in comparison with the base period 2014-2016.

Dataset Overview¶

The data consisted of all countries and regions with different food categories. This data was coupled with production indices from 1961 to 2020. We extracted data on world and Africa prodcution indices for maize and wheat from 2001 to 2020. We then further focused on the main sub-regions in Africa (Eastern Africa, Middle Africa, Northern Africa, Southern Africa and Western Africa) to clarify certain trends.

World and Africa GPI for Maize¶

Maize and Wheat production in Africa saw a wide range of recorded production compared to world data from 2001 to 2020. This could be caused either by wide differences in production from different parts of the continent oro significant fluctuations in production or a combination of both

Trend of World and Africa GPI for Wheat¶

The trends for both Maize and Wheat show that the wide range of GPI for Africa was caused by te relatively larger fluctuations in production of each cereal compared to global production. Fluctuations were more severe in Africa's Wheat production. Acccording to data from the FAO, there was an average 130% increase in Maize production by Africa from 2001 to 2020 while total world production saw an 83% increase within the same period. Africa's Wheat production saw a lower growth at around 37% within the same time period with world's growt even lower at 25%.

Africa GPI for Maize by sub-Region¶

Focusing on the five sub-regions of the African continent, all apart from Northern Africa saw a relatively wider range of both Maize and Wheat production across the 20 years of at least 110 index points. Southern Africa recorded the highest GPI withn the time period for Maize production while Western Africa recorded the highest ever for Wheat. Western Africa also consequently recorded the widest range for wheat production in Africa followed closely by Eastern Africa.

Trend of Africa GPI for Maize and Wheat by sub-Regions¶

The trend below describes the very unhealthy fluctuation in GPI by the African sub-regions for both Maize and Wheat. Southern Africa was the major cause of the entire continents' very wide fluctuations with a major spike in growth from 2016 to 2017 followed by a significant decline the nex two years. All other regions grew relatively steadily till northern Africa had major decline from 2017 through to 2019. It made a significant recovery from 2018 to 2019 but still ended being the only region to end the year 2020 almost at the same GPI as it started with in 2001. Western Africa had the most interesting trend for Wheat production in the African continent. The sub-region had the fastest growth from 2001 to 2011 where it peaked and recorded the highest ever production index at about 160 index points. It the declined almost as fast as it grew through the remainder of the years under study by about 80%.

Percentage Maize Production in Africa by Region at Intervals¶

Southern Africa maintained its position as the major producing region in Africa for Maize for most part of the 20 years under study. The biggest gainer was West Africa who moved from a percentage share of 15% in 2001 to 22.2% by 2020. Nothern Africa dropped the most percentage share from 27% to 16.2%.

Percentage Wheat Production in Africa by Region at Intervals¶

Eastern Africa saw it's percentage share of Africa's total Wheat production more than double across the 20 years moving from 11% to 24.2%. The plots show Western Africa's rise and subsequent fall in percentage contribution.
